Lyde is warned not ‘placito pugnare amori’ by the story of the Danaids and ’ their punishment, and the noble exception of Hypermnestra. The application of the story is not very close. The form of the Ode seems to be a nearer imitation than usual of the construction of an Ode of Pindar; the commeneement by an invocation of Mercury aud the lyre; the accidental way in which, through the recountal of the feats of music, the Danaids are introduced; the myth told at length, but lest to be applied hy the readcr's wit. -Compare 3. 3 and 3. η.

For the story of the Danaids read Aesch. Pr. V. 853-869 and Ov, Her. 14 ‘Hypermnestra Lynceo: which contains frequent reminiscences and expressions of passages in this Ode.
